        -3x \amp \gt 6 \ -2amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by -6.}}
        x \amp \lt \amp \amp \blert{\text{We reverse the direction of the inequality.}}
The graph of the solutions is shown below.
    number line

The vertex is the point (-3,2).  We can find the y-intercept by setting x=0.
    y = \dfrac{-1}{2}(\alert{0}+3)^2-2 = \dfrac{-9}{2}-2 = -6\dfrac{1}{2}
    The y-intercept is the point (0, -6\dfrac{1}{2}). The axis of symmetry is the vertical line x=-3, and there is a symmetric point equidistant from the axis, namely (-6, -6\dfrac{1}{2}). We plot these three points and sketch the parabola through them.
